A better year for migrants?
DUBLIN – Two major lessons emerge from the Mediterranean migration crisis.
Firstly, Europe and the international community apply a cruelly inadequate system to protect the most vulnerable migrants.
Secondly, in the face of the ineffectiveness of this system, populist actors ceaselessly exploit fears to gain political support, undermining liberal and tolerant societies that required 70 years of relentless efforts to build.
That is why it is indispensable that a genuinely active approach be undertaken this year at the European and global levels.
In September next year, UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will convene an extraordinary summit to build a solid global system for protecting the most vulnerable migrants and refugees.
Let's hope that states are ready to engage in a concrete and lasting manner.
This necessary engagement was cruelly lacking during the year 2015.
In fact, the international community would have been able to limit the gravity of the crisis last year if it had provided even the most modest support to the countries on the frontline – Turkey, Lebanon and Jordan – which together host no less than four million refugees.
With approximately 10 billion €, these countries would have been more able to house, feed, and provide education to the refugees, thereby reducing the temptation for an exodus to Europe.
This failure could cost Germany alone up to 21 billion € each year in the times to come.
But the financial implications of the crisis are in no way comparable to its human and political cost.
More than a million people risked their lives last year crossing the Mediterranean, then endured an exhausting journey through the Balkans.
Almost 4,000 migrants lost their lives, with many European countries turning their backs on the survivors by refusing them refuge.
The most cynical politicians exploited the fears of citizens mercilessly, promoting a detestable nationalist vision, either by ignoring or distorting the migrants' life experience.
For example, in the United States, out of the 780,000 refugees installed since September 11, 2001, not a single one was responsible for terrorist acts.
At the same time, immigrants generally pay more taxes than they benefit from social benefits.
And yet, extremist parties are flirting dangerously with the prospect of seizing power in some European countries, and are currently gaining support even within long-standing liberal bastions.
Anti-immigration parties are already in power in Hungary and Poland.
Their success is also leading traditional parties to promote their own anti-immigration policies.
This situation has considerably strained European cooperation.
The EU program aimed at addressing the million refugees arrived on its shores has only allowed for the "relocation" of 190.
Border controls in six Schengen countries have been reinstated, at least provisionally.
In the eyes of the rest of the world, the EU appears today as nationalist and incompetent.
Naturally, the resolution of this crisis does not only concern Europe; responsibility cannot be defined solely by geographical proximity.
Whatever the case, the EU is undoubtedly facing a threat to its own existence today, which it can only overcome by firmly demonstrating the international solidarity and leadership it is capable of.
That is why it is up to the member states to take the initiative by proposing solutions.
The most urgent priority is to establish legal and secure routes allowing refugees to reach Europe.
This is not a matter of asserting that each migrant in need must be welcomed.
It is nonetheless the responsibility of the EU to be more systematically generous in determining the number of refugees to be welcomed, and to use ordered mechanisms to facilitate their entry.
A system like this would protect migrants while safeguarding Europe (by allowing for a full examination of requests).
Beyond a line of approach aimed at dissuading asylum seekers from risking their lives crossing the Mediterranean, such an approach would allow the projection of a picture of solidarity to the frontline countries, which continue to host the majority of refugees.
This aspect is just as important; it would encourage the rest of the international community to contribute to the efforts.
This leads to the second priority of 2016: building a solid global system for the protection of vulnerable refugees and migrants.
This goal will first require more countries to accept hosting refugees.
Over the past few years, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees has only managed to resettle less than 75,000 out of approximately 20 million annual refugees.
Several million of them end up in a situation of prolonged migration, with an estimated average duration of 25 years, prisoners in a kind of purgatory and uncertain about the day of a potential return to their country.
In 2016, it is necessary for developed countries to agree to welcome a cumulative total of nearly one million refugees per year, either through their resettlement or by granting them a humanitarian visa, a student visa, a work visa, or any other type.
Given that Canada has stated it will welcome 50,000 Syrian refugees this year, it is a clearly achievable goal.
At the same time, the international community must support the integration of refugees into major host countries such as Turkey, Kenya, Lebanon, and Jordan.
In their current state, these countries receive only a fraction of the $3,000 to $5,000 annually required for each refugee for housing, food, care, education, and vocational training in the first years of their installation.
And these figures do not take into account the necessary cost of building or upgrading infrastructure.
For example, in Lebanon, the water supply systems are suffering from the massive influx of refugees.
In exchange for financing, host countries could commit to fully integrating refugees into their schools, labor market, and civic institutions.
But the effective integration of migrants will only be possible if European and other countries get rid of their prejudices about migrants.
If they continue to be considered as a burden, or even as a threat to security, reactionary forces will gain ground, depriving new arrivals of opportunities and turning fear into a self-fulfilling prophecy.
On the other hand, if host countries manage to integrate migrants with enthusiasm, everyone will benefit – including those countries (notably through income).
Last month, in Paris, the international community demonstrated that it was capable of subordinating its national interests to a broader global objective: the fight against climate change.
In 2016, it is necessary for a similar effort to aim at building a better system for protecting migrants.
This is a matter of life and death for some 20 million refugees, for several million other vulnerable migrants – as well as a profound test of democratic societies' civic health worldwide.
